<heading bold="true" box="[151,790,366,393]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" reason="1">
<taxonomicName authority="Kurshakov &amp; Zolotuhin, 2013" authorityName="Kurshakov &amp; Zolotuhin" authorityYear="2013" box="[151,790,366,393]" class="Insecta" family="Limacodidae" genus="Strigivenifera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eborea">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,790,366,393]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,406,366,393]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">Strigivenifera eborea</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Kurshakov, P. A. &amp; Zolotuhin, V. V." box="[414,790,366,393]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" pagination="904 - 919" refId="ref6695" refString="Kurshakov, P. A. &amp; Zolotuhin, V. V. (2013) A review of the genus Strigivenifera Hering, 1937 (Lepidoptera, Chrysopolomidae) with a description of ten new species. Entomological Review, 93 (7), 904 - 919. https: // doi. org / 10.1134 / S 0013873813070142" type="journal article" year="2013">Kurshakov &amp; Zolotuhin, 2013</bibRefCitation>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="54" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,439,1545]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">
Another problematic set of species which is addressed here is 
<taxonomicName authority="Kurshakov &amp; Zolotuhin, 2013" authorityName="Kurshakov &amp; Zolotuhin" authorityYear="2013" box="[847,1298,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Limacodidae" genus="Strigivenifera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eborea">
<emphasis box="[847,952,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">S. eborea</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Kurshakov, P. A. &amp; Zolotuhin, V. V." box="[959,1298,439,465]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" pagination="904 - 919" refId="ref6695" refString="Kurshakov, P. A. &amp; Zolotuhin, V. V. (2013) A review of the genus Strigivenifera Hering, 1937 (Lepidoptera, Chrysopolomidae) with a description of ten new species. Entomological Review, 93 (7), 904 - 919. https: // doi. org / 10.1134 / S 0013873813070142" type="journal article" year="2013">Kurshakov &amp; Zolotuhin, 2013</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">S. ocellaris</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Kurshakov, P. A. &amp; Zolotuhin, V. V." box="[209,552,475,501]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" pagination="904 - 919" refId="ref6695" refString="Kurshakov, P. A. &amp; Zolotuhin, V. V. (2013) A review of the genus Strigivenifera Hering, 1937 (Lepidoptera, Chrysopolomidae) with a description of ten new species. Entomological Review, 93 (7), 904 - 919. https: // doi. org / 10.1134 / S 0013873813070142" type="journal article" year="2013">Kurshakov &amp; Zolotuhin, 2013</bibRefCitation>
. Both of these taxa were described from 
<collectingCountry box="[1006,1138,475,501]" name="Ivory Coast" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">Ivory Coast</collectingCountry>
(note the TL of the former should be Grand-Béréby and the latter Danané but both are misspelt/mis-transcribed in the original description) and exist in sympatry throughout West Africa. In the male genitalia, the clasping apparatus and aedeagus are identical, with the only difference being the presence of one or two very small, thin cornuti on the aedeagus in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kurshakov &amp; Zolotuhin" authorityYear="2013" box="[1322,1429,583,609]" class="Insecta" family="Limacodidae" genus="Strigivenifera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eborea">
<emphasis box="[1322,1429,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">S. eborea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is absent in the related species. Indeed, the presence or absence of cornuti is in most cases a very good species character (
<bibRefCitation author="Anzaldo, S. S. &amp; Dombroskie, J. &amp; Brown, J. W." box="[270,502,655,681]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" pagination="1 - 31" refId="ref6172" refString="Anzaldo, S. S., Dombroskie, J. &amp; Brown, J. W. (2014) Morphological variation, taxonomic distribution, and phylogenetic significance of cornuti in Tortricinae (Lepidoptera: Tortricidae). Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington, 116 (1), 1 - 31. https: // doi. org / 10.4289 / 0013 - 8797.116.1.1" type="journal article" year="2014">
Anzaldo 
<emphasis box="[375,426,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">et al</emphasis>
. 2014
</bibRefCitation>
). However, through dissections of barcoded specimens from near the type locality (BOLD process ids./gen. slide Nos.: ANLMN8466-21/TT 123; ANLMN8471-21/TT 114; ANLMN8472/TT 115; ANLMN8477-21/TT 116; ANLMN8465-21/TT 141; ANLMN8478-21/TT 140) which recovered with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kurshakov &amp; Zolotuhin" authorityYear="2013" box="[1329,1437,727,753]" class="Insecta" family="Limacodidae" genus="Strigivenifera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eborea">
<emphasis box="[1329,1437,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">S. eborea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<typeStatus box="[151,258,763,789]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">paratypes</typeStatus>
(BOLD process ids.: LIMBC838-11; LIMBC839-11), this character trait was determined to be insufficient for diagnosing the two species, with two of these specimens possessing a single cornutus on the aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[159,266,834,861]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1690,1714]" captionTargetBox="[279,1308,189,1652]" captionTargetId="figure-27@4.[268,1319,179,1664]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–13. Adult male Strigivenifera (deposited at ANHRT unless otherwise stated). 1. S. albidiscalis, DRC (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN8462-21/TT 118); 2. S. albidiscalis, Zambia (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN8454- 21/TT 111); 3. S. albidiscalis, Zambia (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN8460-21/TT 112); 4. S. eborea, Ivory Coast (BOLD process id./gen. slide No. ANLMN8471-21/TT 114); 5. S. eborea, Sierra Leone (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN8472/TT 115); 6. S. eborea, Ivory Coast (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN8466-21/TT 123); 7. S. eborea, Ivory Coast (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN8465-21/TT 141); 8. S. smithi sp. n., HT, Sierra Leone (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN8475-21/TT 122); 9. S. smithi sp. n., PT, Sierra Leone (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: AN- LMN8474/TT 121), 10. S. smithi sp. n., PT, Sierra Leone (gen. slide No.: TT 139); 11. S. bartschi (PT of S. tatooifera), DRC (gen. slide No.: CHRY-11-52) (RMCA); 12. S. bartschi, DRC (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN7892-21/TT 124); 13. S. bartschi, DRC (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN7890-21/TT 125)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876376" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876376/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">Figs. 4–5</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[278,348,835,861]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–20" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1834,1858]" captionTargetBox="[266,1313,198,1804]" captionTargetId="figure-16@5.[260,1327,181,1810]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 14–20. Male genitalia of Strigivenifera (a. clasping apparatus; b. aedeagus). 14. S. albidiscalis, DRC (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN8462-21/TT 118); 15. S. albidiscalis, Zambia (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN8454-21/ TT 111); 16. S. albidiscalis, Zambia (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN8460-21/TT 112); 17. S. eborea, Ivory Coast (BOLD process id./gen. slide No. ANLMN8471-21/TT 114); 18. S. eborea, Sierra Leone (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN8472/TT 115); 19. S. eborea, Ivory Coast (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN8466-21/TT 123); 20. S. eborea, Ivory Coast (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN8465-21/TT 141)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876378" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876378/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">17–18</figureCitation>
) whilst it was absent in the others (
<figureCitation box="[740,847,835,861]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1690,1714]" captionTargetBox="[279,1308,189,1652]" captionTargetId="figure-27@4.[268,1319,179,1664]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–13. Adult male Strigivenifera (deposited at ANHRT unless otherwise stated). 1. S. albidiscalis, DRC (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN8462-21/TT 118); 2. S. albidiscalis, Zambia (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN8454- 21/TT 111); 3. S. albidiscalis, Zambia (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN8460-21/TT 112); 4. S. eborea, Ivory Coast (BOLD process id./gen. slide No. ANLMN8471-21/TT 114); 5. S. eborea, Sierra Leone (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN8472/TT 115); 6. S. eborea, Ivory Coast (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN8466-21/TT 123); 7. S. eborea, Ivory Coast (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN8465-21/TT 141); 8. S. smithi sp. n., HT, Sierra Leone (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN8475-21/TT 122); 9. S. smithi sp. n., PT, Sierra Leone (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: AN- LMN8474/TT 121), 10. S. smithi sp. n., PT, Sierra Leone (gen. slide No.: TT 139); 11. S. bartschi (PT of S. tatooifera), DRC (gen. slide No.: CHRY-11-52) (RMCA); 12. S. bartschi, DRC (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN7892-21/TT 124); 13. S. bartschi, DRC (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN7890-21/TT 125)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876376" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876376/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">Figs. 6–7</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[858,932,835,861]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–20" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1834,1858]" captionTargetBox="[266,1313,198,1804]" captionTargetId="figure-16@5.[260,1327,181,1810]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 14–20. Male genitalia of Strigivenifera (a. clasping apparatus; b. aedeagus). 14. S. albidiscalis, DRC (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN8462-21/TT 118); 15. S. albidiscalis, Zambia (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN8454-21/ TT 111); 16. S. albidiscalis, Zambia (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN8460-21/TT 112); 17. S. eborea, Ivory Coast (BOLD process id./gen. slide No. ANLMN8471-21/TT 114); 18. S. eborea, Sierra Leone (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN8472/TT 115); 19. S. eborea, Ivory Coast (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN8466-21/TT 123); 20. S. eborea, Ivory Coast (BOLD process id./gen. slide No.: ANLMN8465-21/TT 141)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876378" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876378/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">19–20</figureCitation>
); it should be noted that every other aspect of the genital morphology was identical. The reason why the cornuti may not be present in some specimens is speculative; it may just be a variable feature (e.g. in 
<bibRefCitation author="Przystalkowska, A. &amp; Przybylowicz, L." box="[645,1075,907,933]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" pagination="203 - 210" refId="ref6941" refString="Przystalkowska, A. &amp; Przybylowicz, L. (2018) Balacra Walker, 1856 (Lepidoptera: Erebidae: Arctiinae: Syntomini) from Togo - A Taxonomic and Faunistic Review. Annales Zoologici, 68 (2), 203 - 210. https: // doi. org / 10.3161 / 00034541 ANZ 2018.68.2.001" type="journal article" year="2018">Przystałkowska &amp; Przybyłowicz 2018</bibRefCitation>
), or it may have been lost during copulation (as suggested by Evenden 
<emphasis box="[573,622,943,969]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">et al</emphasis>
. 2003) or the transportation of dried specimens. The latter explanation is probable as the cornuti of this species is often singular and incredibly thin, and thus could be easily broken when the juxta and the aedeagus protrudes out of the end of the abdomen as observed in the vast majority of specimens in the ANHRT collections (
<figureCitation box="[458,542,1051,1077]" captionStart="FIGURE 27" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1959,1983]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,1533,1936]" captionTargetId="figure-586@7.[152,1436,1533,1936]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 27. Images showing the aedeagus and juxta lobes protruding out of the end of the abdomen in an S. eborea specimen from Ivory Coast (ANHRT): a. lateral view, b. posterior angle." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876382" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876382/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,439,1545]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">
For these reasons, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kurshakov &amp; Zolotuhin" authorityYear="2013" box="[405,509,1087,1113]" class="Insecta" family="Limacodidae" genus="Strigivenifera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eborea">
<emphasis box="[405,509,1087,1113]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">S. eborea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[562,687,1087,1113]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">S. ocellaris</emphasis>
are treated as conspecific and a new synonymy is presented herein: 
<emphasis box="[151,277,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">S. ocellaris</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Kurshakov, P. A. &amp; Zolotuhin, V. V." box="[284,623,1123,1149]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" pagination="904 - 919" refId="ref6695" refString="Kurshakov, P. A. &amp; Zolotuhin, V. V. (2013) A review of the genus Strigivenifera Hering, 1937 (Lepidoptera, Chrysopolomidae) with a description of ten new species. Entomological Review, 93 (7), 904 - 919. https: // doi. org / 10.1134 / S 0013873813070142" type="journal article" year="2013">Kurshakov &amp; Zolotuhin, 2013</bibRefCitation>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[630,708,1123,1149]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">syn. n.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,439,1545]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">
Interestingly, the single 
<typeStatus box="[480,576,1159,1185]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">paratype</typeStatus>
specimen of 
<emphasis box="[739,869,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">S. ocellaris</emphasis>
(BOLD process id.: LIMBC850-11) included in 
<bibRefCitation author="Kurshakov, P. A. &amp; Zolotuhin, V. V." box="[151,522,1195,1221]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" pagination="904 - 919" refId="ref6695" refString="Kurshakov, P. A. &amp; Zolotuhin, V. V. (2013) A review of the genus Strigivenifera Hering, 1937 (Lepidoptera, Chrysopolomidae) with a description of ten new species. Entomological Review, 93 (7), 904 - 919. https: // doi. org / 10.1134 / S 0013873813070142" type="journal article" year="2013">Kurshakov &amp; Zolotuhin’s (2013)</bibRefCitation>
phylogeny from the 
<collectingRegion box="[759,910,1195,1221]" country="Sierra Leone" name="Western" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">Western Area</collectingRegion>
Peninsula of 
<collectingCountry box="[1065,1210,1195,1221]" name="Sierra Leone" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">Sierra Leone</collectingCountry>
was recovered with two other ANHRT specimens (BOLD process ids./gen. slide Nos.: ANLMN8474-21/TT 121; ANLMN8475-21/TT 122) from the same locality, in a completely separate clade to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kurshakov &amp; Zolotuhin" authorityYear="2013" box="[850,955,1267,1293]" class="Insecta" family="Limacodidae" genus="Strigivenifera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eborea">
<emphasis box="[850,955,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">S. eborea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Given that 
<emphasis box="[1094,1220,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">S. ocellaris</emphasis>
has here been synonymised with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kurshakov &amp; Zolotuhin" authorityYear="2013" box="[322,426,1303,1329]" class="Insecta" family="Limacodidae" genus="Strigivenifera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eborea">
<emphasis box="[322,426,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">S. eborea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, an undescribed species exists in apparent allopatry to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kurshakov &amp; Zolotuhin" authorityYear="2013" box="[1032,1135,1303,1329]" class="Insecta" family="Limacodidae" genus="Strigivenifera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eborea">
<emphasis box="[1032,1135,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">S. eborea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It is likely that 
<bibRefCitation author="Kurshakov, P. A. &amp; Zolotuhin, V. V." pageId="3" pageNumber="54" pagination="904 - 919" refId="ref6695" refString="Kurshakov, P. A. &amp; Zolotuhin, V. V. (2013) A review of the genus Strigivenifera Hering, 1937 (Lepidoptera, Chrysopolomidae) with a description of ten new species. Entomological Review, 93 (7), 904 - 919. https: // doi. org / 10.1134 / S 0013873813070142" type="journal article" year="2013">Kurshakov &amp; Zolotuhin (2013)</bibRefCitation>
made an incorrect assumption regarding the specific characters of 
<emphasis box="[1140,1268,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">S. ocellaris</emphasis>
based on their single barcoded specimen but it is difficult to understand why they did not designate that barcoded specimen as the 
<typeStatus box="[151,253,1411,1437]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">holotype</typeStatus>
. The difference in DNA with the otherwise near-identical West African species is striking, with an APWD of 6.2%, and even more unexpectedly, the 
<collectingRegion box="[638,790,1447,1473]" country="Sierra Leone" name="Western" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">Western Area</collectingRegion>
Peninsula specimens recovered as a sister to the Central African 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kurshakov &amp; Zolotuhin" authorityYear="2013" box="[243,399,1483,1509]" class="Insecta" family="Limacodidae" genus="Strigivenifera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albidiscalis">
<emphasis box="[243,399,1483,1509]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">S. albidiscalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with APWD of 5.9% albeit with weak support values. Based on this evidence, the description of a new species 
<taxonomicName authority="Taberer, 2022" authorityName="Taberer" authorityYear="2022" box="[342,571,1519,1545]" class="Insecta" family="Limacodidae" genus="Strigivenifera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="smithi" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[342,571,1519,1545]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">Strigivenifera smithi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[579,642,1519,1545]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[579,642,1519,1545]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is provided herein:
</paragraph>
